rtainment.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cp\u003eWhen \u003ca href=\"https://www.polygon.com/news/597569/gta-6-delay-release-date\"\u003eRockstar Games delayed\u003c/a\u003e \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.polygon.com/23952805/gta-6-grand-theft-auto-leaks-release-date-trailer\"\u003eGrand Theft Auto 6\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e into 2026, it likely came as a big relief to publishers who had anything on their slate for the back half of 2025. But 2026 is already shaping up to be an exciting, crowded year of big game releases, even without \u003cem\u003eGTA 6\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eIn addition to Rockstar’s ambitious new crime epic, we can expect Playground Games’ new \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.polygon.com/23755219/new-fable-xbox-release-date-playground-games\"\u003eFable\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e (finally!), Housemarque’s \u003cem\u003eReturnal\u003c/em\u003e follow-up \u003cem\u003eSaros\u003c/em\u003e, FromSoftware’s \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.polygon.com/nintendo-switch-2/550315/fromsoftware-new-game-the-duskbloods-switch-2-direct\"\u003eThe Duskbloods\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e, the \u003ca href=\"https://www.polygon.com/gaming/524098/onimusha-way-of-the-sword-toshiro-mifune-capcom\"\u003ereturn of Capcom’s Onimusha franchise\u003c/a\u003e, and (at least) two long-awaited new franchise entries from Nintendo: \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.polygon.com/gaming/547833/new-rhythm-heaven-groove-announced\"\u003eRhythm Heaven Groove\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e and \u003cem\u003eTomodachi Life: Living the Dream\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eBeyond sequels, there are plenty of promising original games on the horizon, like role-playing game \u003cem\u003eSacriFire\u003c/em\u003e, Warren Spector’s stealth-action PvPvE game \u003cem\u003eThick As Thieves\u003c/em\u003e, and Animal Crossing-but-make-it-vampires indie \u003cem\u003eMoonlight 